multiphase (experimental)
=========================

The agent supports five multiphase solvers via legacy monolithic
prompt packs:

  - interFoam — incompressible two-phase VOF (water + air sloshing,
    free-surface flows, dam breaks).
  - interIsoFoam — incompressible two-phase with isoAdvector
    interface capture (sharper interface than the standard VOF).
  - compressibleInterFoam — compressible two-phase VOF
    (boiling, condensation, cavitation, phase-change).
  - compressibleInterIsoFoam — compressible isoAdvector variant.
  - compressibleMultiphaseInterFoam — N-phase compressible VOF.


status
------

These solvers haven't been ported to the plugin package format yet.
They still use the legacy monolithic .md files under
simd_agent/prompts/packs/simd/solvers/multiphase/ and the fallback
branch in build_required_files_list().

What that means for you:

  - They work — the agent can pick them, generate cases for
    them, and self-heal them, with the same orchestrator as the
    single-region path.
  - The validators are thinner — fewer auto-fixes for known
    pitfalls (sigma block, phase pair sub-dicts, etc.).
  - The fluid registry is hardcoded — switching liquids needs
    edits in genai_codegen.py:_eos_for_liquid() rather than a
    plugin attribute.


when to use them
----------------

  - interFoam / interIsoFoam — incompressible free-surface
    problems. Water-air interfaces dominated by gravity. Standard
    benchmark cases (dam break, sloshing tank).

  - compressibleInterFoam — anywhere phase change happens at
    speed: cryogenic regasifiers (LN2 → GN2), boiling channels,
    cavitating propellers, evaporating sprays. The chtMultiRegion
    family can't capture latent heat or the liquid→vapor density
    drop; this one can.

  - compressibleMultiphaseInterFoam — three or more phases
    (e.g. liquid + vapor + non-condensable air). Heavier
    numerically, more knobs.


known pitfalls the validators enforce
-------------------------------------

A few captured in simd_agent/run/genai_codegen.py:

  - compressibleInterFoam and friends need BOTH 0/p AND
    0/p_rgh. 0/p is declared MUST_READ. The validator
    synthesizes whichever is missing.

  - compressibleInterFoam: nOuterCorrectors ≥ 2 (PIMPLE not
    PISO). icoPolynomial ρ(T) has zero acoustic compressibility,
    so PISO mode leaves T-ρ-p-U coupling unresolved and Co blows
    up. momentumPredictor yes, nNonOrthogonalCorrectors ≥ 1.

  - compressibleInterFoam: maxCo 0.5, NOT 1.0 in controlDict.
    At Co=1 the limiter reacts too late to prevent divergence.

  - Native liquidProperties pair (e.g. liquidNitrogen) MUST use
    sensibleInternalEnergy (not sensibleEnthalpy). The latter
    causes SIGFPE in heRhoThermo constructor. The validator
    auto-corrects: sensibleEnthalpy → sensibleInternalEnergy,
    hConst → eConst, Cp → Cv for the vapour side.


thermophysical setup for compressible multiphase
-------------------------------------------------

Three files instead of one:

  - constant/thermophysicalProperties — base file with phases /
    pMin / sigma.
  - constant/thermophysicalProperties.<liquid> — per-phase
    liquid file (native liquidProperties).
  - constant/thermophysicalProperties.<vapour> — per-phase
    vapour file (perfectGas + eConst + Cv).

Phase names are derived from the fluid name (LN2 →
liquidNitrogen / nitrogenVapour, LH2 → liquidHydrogen /
hydrogenVapour, LOX → liquidOxygen / oxygenVapour).


what's missing
--------------

  - Plugin port. These should be self-contained directories
    under simd_agent/solvers/multiphase/<name>/ mirroring the
    single-region plugins. PRs welcome — see
    adding-a-solver for the contract.

  - Phase-change detection in precheck. When a user prompts a
    regasifier ("LN2 inlet at 77 K, water at 290 K"), the precheck
    should flag phase_change_detected: true and route to
    compressibleInterFoam instead of chtMultiRegionSimpleFoam.
    Today the agent picks the single-phase CHT solver and silently
    underestimates heat capacity.

  - Validation parity with single-region. The new plugin-based
    validators have ~25 auto-fix checks; the multiphase legacy
    path has ~6. Bringing the rest over is good first-issue work.
